Lincolnshire, England":"Moulton, Lincolnshire, England","Revesby, Lincolnshire, England":"Revesby, Lincolnshire, England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Multon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Moulton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Moulton","meanings":["English (mainly Cheshire and Lancashire): habitational name from one or more of the places called Moulton (Cheshire, Lincolnshire, Norfolk, Northamptonshire, Staffordshire, Suffolk, North Yorkshire), most of which are named with the Old English personal name <i>Mūl(a)</i>, the Old Norse personal name <i>Múli</i>, or Old English <i>mūl</i> ‘mule’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."]}]},{"name":"Lambert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which is from an Old French given name of Germanic origin, from <i>land</i> ‘land, territory’ + <i>beorht</i> ‘famous’. This was introduced to Britain by the Normans, but its frequency in Britain in later centuries owed something to immigrants from the Low Countries, and it continued in occasional use into the 18th century at least.  St Lambert of Maastricht  was a 7th-century saint who aided  St Willibrord  in his evangelical work."],"variants":[{"name":"Lammert","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which is from an Old French given name of Germanic origin, from <i>land</i> ‘land, territory’ + <i>beorht</i> ‘famous’. This was introduced to Britain by the Normans, but its frequency in Britain in later centuries owed something to immigrants from the Low Countries, and it continued in occasional use into the 18th century at least.  St Lambert of Maastricht  was a 7th-century saint who aided  St Willibrord  in his evangelical work."]},{"name":"Lamprecht","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which is from an Old French given name of Germanic origin, from <i>land</i> ‘land, territory’ + <i>beorht</i> ‘famous’. This was introduced to Britain by the Normans, but its frequency in Britain in later centuries owed something to immigrants from the Low Countries, and it continued in occasional use into the 18th century at least.  St Lambert of Maastricht  was a 7th-century saint who aided  St Willibrord  in his evangelical work."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lambert de Multon I was born in 1121, in Revesby, Lincolnshire, England as the son of Thomas de Multon. He married Hawise de Briwere about 1143, in Lincolnshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 3 daughters. He died in 1167, in Moulton, Lincolnshire, England, at the age of 46, and was buried in Spalding, Lincolnshire, England."},"et":{"1121–1167":"1121–1167","1130–1166":"1130–1166","1146–1201":"1146–1201","1150–1217":"1150–1217","1155–Male":"1155–Surnud","1160–Female":"1160–Surnud","1165–1220":"1165–1220","1100–1140":"1100–1140","1121":"1121","1220":"1220","1165":"1165","1130":"1130","1140":"1140","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","1217":"1217","1146":"1146","1201":"1201","1167":"1167","Abt 1165":"umbes 1165","1166":"1166","1100":"1100","1155":"1155","about 1143":"umbes 1143","about 1155":"umbes 1155","Irby on Humber, Lincolnshire, Engl